President Joe Biden has appointed several individuals to key regional leadership roles at the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) at the Department of Homeland Security. These regional appointees will play a crucial role in the President's efforts to rebuild communities impacted by the pandemic, economic recovery, and climate change. The appointments aim to bring deep expertise in their respective issue areas and establish critical relationships with federal, state, tribal, and local leaders. The appointees also represent the diversity of America and the communities they serve. The USDA appointees include State Executive Directors and State Directors for the Farm Service Agency and Rural Development. The EPA appointee is the Regional Administrator for Region 1, which covers Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, and Vermont. The FEMA appointee is the Regional Administrator for Region 10, which covers Alaska, Idaho, Oregon, and Washington.